Latest Articles






DealBook

                    SPX Reaches Accord With Relational Over Board Seats                











DealBook

                    SPX Sells Auto Tools Business for $1.15 Billion                
The SPX Corporation, an industrial conglomerate, said on Tuesday that it had agreed to sell its auto tools and solutions business to Robert Bosch of Germany for $1.15 billion in cash.










COMPANY NEWS

                    GENERAL ELECTRIC WILL BUY SAFETY UNIT FROM SPX                
The General Electric Company said yesterday that it had agreed to buy the Edwards Systems Technology business of the SPX Corporation for $1.4 billion in cash to add fire detection and building safety systems to its three-year-old security unit. General Electric will get ''significant'' cost savings, said William Woodburn, chief executive of GE Infrastructure, the unit buying Edwards. SPX, which is based in Charlotte, N.C., said that it would use the proceeds to pay debt and buy back stock. General Electric will be able to broaden its security offerings and tap what it estimates is a $15 billion industry for fire and building-system products. General Electric is based in Fairfield, Conn.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX SAYS REVENUE ROSE MORE THAN EXPECTED                
SPX Corporation, a maker of power transformers, broadcast antennas and industrial equipment, said that fourth-quarter revenue rose about 10 percent from the year-earlier period, helped by acquisitions and rising demand. SPX said it previously forecast a 6 percent increase. Full-year profit from continuing operations was at least $3.40 a share, in line with estimates, the company said. In 2002, SPX reported a profit of $3.33 a share, excluding a change in accounting. Excluding acquisitions, sales in the fourth quarter would have risen about 6 percent, the company said. Fourth-quarter sales climbed 18 percent at SPX's service-solutions business and 12 percent at the flow-technology unit, the company said. SPX is based in Charlotte, N.C.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX TO RECORD $12 MILLION EXPENSE TO REDUCE DEBT                
SPX, which makes power transformers, broadcast antennas and industrial equipment, said yesterday that it would record a $12 million pretax expense this year because of costs to pay debt. The company, based in Charlotte, N.C., plans to pay $200 million of a bank loan on Dec. 31 and terminate an equal amount in interest rate swaps. The forecast for full-year profit from continuing operations of at least $3.40 is unchanged, SPX said in a statement.











                    Microsoft to Pay $60 Million Settlement                
Microsoft has agreed to pay $60 million to the Imagexpo unit of the SPX Corporation to end a legal fight over a patent for real-time conferencing software. A jury in Richmond, Va., in November told Microsoft to pay Imagexpo $62.3 million for impermissibly using the company's patented technology in the NetMeeting Whiteboard features in Microsoft programs. That amount could have been tripled, because the jury determined that Microsoft's use of the Imagexpo's invention was intentional.











                    Technology Briefing | Deals: Computer Network Agrees To Buy Inrange                
The Computer Network Technology Corporation, which provides software and hardware for computer storage networks, agreed yesterday to buy the Inrange Technologies Corporation for about $190 million in cash, to add networking services. Computer Network will pay $2.31 a share for Inrange, a unit of the SPX Corporation, and expects the purchase to increase earnings this year by at least 10 percent, the company said. The price is 4.1 percent above Inrange's closing price Friday of $2.22. The purchase will allow Computer Network to provide more products that help speed connections between computer and telecommunications networks, the company said. As a result of the acquisition, Computer Network will raise its 2003 profit forecast from the 17-cent average estimate of analysts polled by Thomson Financial, the chairman and chief executive officer, Thomas G. Hudson, said. Shares of Computer Network fell $1.95, or more than 27 percent, to $5.10. Inrange shares rose 6 cents, to $2.28. Computer Network plans to cut an undisclosed number of sales, information technology and administrative jobs as part of the purchase, Mr. Hudson said, without being more specific.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX BUYS VANCE INTERNATIONAL FOR $67 MILLION                
The SPX Corporation, whose security unit provides security services, bought a closely held security provider, Vance International Inc., for $67 million. SPX said Vance had revenue of about $95 million a year and would join SPX's Security and Investigations unit. Under the Vance trade name, the SPX unit will focus on protection services and security consulting.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SNAP-ON, A TOOLS CONCERN, TO PAY SPX $44 MILLION                
Snap-On Inc. said it would pay $44 million to a rival, the SPX Corporation, after a federal arbitrator decided it had improperly used SPX's patented technology for equipment that tests car engines. Snap-On, which makes tools for the automotive maintenance industry, said it would set aside $27.9 million, or 48 cents a share, against fourth-quarter earnings to pay the after-tax cost of the arbitration award. The dispute started in 1996, when Snap-On, which is based in Pleasant Prairie, Wis., accused SPX of infringing its patents and improperly hiring away an executive from the Sun Electric Corporation, a company that Snap-On bought in 1992. SPX, of Muskegon, Mich., countersued, accusing Snap-On of infringing on its patents.











                    Inrange Chief Executive Resigns Posts                
The Inrange Technologies Corporation, the networking- and switching-equipment maker spun off by the SPX Corporation, said today that its chief executive and president, Greg Grodhaus, had resigned. The stock fell 17 percent.















                    SPX to Lay Off 500 More                
The SPX Corporation, which owns dozens of companies that make brakes, hydraulic gear and fiber optic equipment, said today that third-quarter earnings fell and that it would lay off an additional 500 workers. Net income fell to $59.2 million, or $1.45 a share, from $62.7 million, or $1.94, a year earlier, the company said. SPX, which in May bought United Dominion Industries for $2.58 billion, said revenue almost doubled, to $1.22 billion from $645.1 million. SPX now plans to cut 2,500 jobs by May.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX, A MAKER OF INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTS, TO BUY KENDRO                
The SPX Corporation, a maker of industrial products that sold its motor unit last month, agreed to buy Kendro Laboratory Products, which makes products for the life-sciences industry, for $320 million. Kendro, which has annual revenue of more than $200 million, makes centrifuges, incubators, ovens and freezers for the pharmaceutical, biochemistry and molecular biology industries. SPX, which is based in Muskegon, Mich., is adding products to expand its Revco life-sciences unit. Kendro's incubators are used to grow cells for disease and drug research, the freezers are used by blood banks and sperm banks and the centrifuges spin blood to separate the components, an SPX spokeswoman, Tina Betlejewski, said. Kendro, which is based in Newtown, Conn., has more than 1,200 employees, and sells products under the Heraeus, Sorvall and CARR brand names.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX SAYS IT WILL ACQUIRE VSI HOLDINGS                
The SPX Corporation, a maker of industrial and automotive products, said it will acquire VSI Holdings for about $146 million to gain VSI's Internet development products. SPX said it will also assume about $51 million in debt. Shareholders of VSI, which is based in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., have the option of exchanging their shares for SPX stock or a combination of stock and cash. SPX, based in Muskegon, Mich., has purchased businesses recently to reduce its dependence on sales related to the automotive industry.











                    Car Dealers Sue, Saying Emission Testing Gear Has Problems                
Car dealers in the metropolitan area, frustrated over what they say is the high failure rate of a new generation of machines testing auto emissions, sued three manufacturers of the equipment yesterday. In filing the lawsuit, the Greater New York State Auto Dealers Association said that cars spewing pollutants were not being weeded out at any greater rate by the new machines, known as dynamometers, because the machines had so many problems.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX TO SELL BEST POWER UNIT TO INVENSYS                
The SPX Corporation signed an agreement yesterday to sell its Best Power subsidiary, which makes power systems that protect computers, information networks and other systems from power-line disturbances, to Invensys P.L.C., the British-based electronics and engineering company. The purchase price is $240 million. SPX provides a wide range of niche products to industrial customers, ranging from auto components to data networking systems. Best Power is based in Necedah, Wis. Shares of SPX, based in Muskegon, Mich., slipped $2.125, to $79.125.











                    SPX Planning $2 Billion Deal for General Signal                
The SPX Corporation is expected to announce today that it is acquiring the General Signal Corporation, a diversified manufacturer, for about $2 billion in stock and cash, according to people close to the deal. The acquisition will expand SPX well beyond the automotive parts and tools that it manufactures. General Signal, which is based in Stamford, Conn., has 15 niche businesses, only one of which is automotive. Its products include mixers, valves, manufacturing equipment, freezers, power transformers and fire-detection equipment.











                    Metro Business; SPX Drops Offer for Echlin                
The SPX Corporation yesterday withdrew its hostile takeover bid for rival auto-parts maker Echlin Inc. of Branford, Conn., two days after Echlin agreed to be bought by Dana Corporation in a friendly $4 billion acquisition. SPX, a Muskegon, Mich., maker of auto parts, had announced its bid in February. Echlin tried to thwart SPX, first through the Connecticut Legislature and then in Federal court.











                    Dana Offers $3.6 Billion in Stock for Echlin                
The Dana Corporation, one of the largest domestic makers of automotive parts and supplies, made a friendly $3.6 billion acquisition offer yesterday for its competitor Echlin Inc., topping a hostile $3.1 billion bid from the SPX Corporation. If approved by shareholders and regulators, the offer could end a battle for control of Echlin that began when SPX, which is based in Muskegon, Mich., began a takeover attempt in February. Then, SPX, which sells auto parts and diagnostic equipment, offered holders $48 a share in cash and stock after Echlin management spurned friendly overtures last year.











                    Metro Business; SPX Begins Echlin Offer                
The SPX Corporation formally began yesterday its exchange offer to take over Echlin Inc., the auto parts maufacturer based in Branford, Conn. Under the terms of the offer, Echlin shareholders would receive $12 in cash plus 0.4796 of an SPX share for each share of Echlin stock tendered. Based on the $72.375 a share closing price of SPX stock yesterday, the deal is valued at $46.71 a share, or a total of about $3 billion. Echlin stock closed yesterday at $47.315.











                    SPX Is Seeking Vote On Its Bid for Echlin                
The SPX Corporation asked a Federal court in Connecticut today to force Echlin Inc. to set a date by April 24 for a special meeting of shareholders to vote on new directors who favor SPX's hostile $3 billion takeover bid. Echlin recently said that a Coopers & Lybrand audit showed that only about 2 percent of the Echlin shares claimed by SPX represented ''valid'' demands for a special meeting that needs a minimum of 35 percent shareholder backing. SPX said it had the support of more than 43 percent of Echlin's outstanding shares.










