DealBook

                    SPX Reaches Accord With Relational Over Board Seats                











DealBook

                    SPX Sells Auto Tools Business for $1.15 Billion                
The SPX Corporation, an industrial conglomerate, said on Tuesday that it had agreed to sell its auto tools and solutions business to Robert Bosch of Germany for $1.15 billion in cash.










COMPANY NEWS

                    GENERAL ELECTRIC WILL BUY SAFETY UNIT FROM SPX                
The General Electric Company said yesterday that it had agreed to buy the Edwards Systems Technology business of the SPX Corporation for $1.4 billion in cash to add fire detection and building safety systems to its three-year-old security unit. General Electric will get ''significant'' cost savings, said William Woodburn, chief executive of GE Infrastructure, the unit buying Edwards. SPX, which is based in Charlotte, N.C., said that it would use the proceeds to pay debt and buy back stock. General Electric will be able to broaden its security offerings and tap what it estimates is a $15 billion industry for fire and building-system products. General Electric is based in Fairfield, Conn.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX SAYS REVENUE ROSE MORE THAN EXPECTED                
SPX Corporation, a maker of power transformers, broadcast antennas and industrial equipment, said that fourth-quarter revenue rose about 10 percent from the year-earlier period, helped by acquisitions and rising demand. SPX said it previously forecast a 6 percent increase. Full-year profit from continuing operations was at least $3.40 a share, in line with estimates, the company said. In 2002, SPX reported a profit of $3.33 a share, excluding a change in accounting. Excluding acquisitions, sales in the fourth quarter would have risen about 6 percent, the company said. Fourth-quarter sales climbed 18 percent at SPX's service-solutions business and 12 percent at the flow-technology unit, the company said. SPX is based in Charlotte, N.C.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SPX TO RECORD $12 MILLION EXPENSE TO REDUCE DEBT                
SPX, which makes power transformers, broadcast antennas and industrial equipment, said yesterday that it would record a $12 million pretax expense this year because of costs to pay debt. The company, based in Charlotte, N.C., plans to pay $200 million of a bank loan on Dec. 31 and terminate an equal amount in interest rate swaps. The forecast for full-year profit from continuing operations of at least $3.40 is unchanged, SPX said in a statement.











                    Microsoft to Pay $60 Million Settlement                
Microsoft has agreed to pay $60 million to the Imagexpo unit of the SPX Corporation to end a legal fight over a patent for real-time conferencing software. A jury in Richmond, Va., in November told Microsoft to pay Imagexpo $62.3 million for impermissibly using the company's patented technology in the NetMeeting Whiteboard features in Microsoft programs. That amount could have been tripled, because the jury determined that Microsoft's use of the Imagexpo's invention was intentional.











