                The two companies formed by SPX's proposed split would remain in Charlotte, sharing space… more 

                NANCY PIERCE            






SPX Corp. (NYSE:SPW) plans to spin off its dominant flow technology operations and create a stand-alone company from that business, leaving the remaining company as an infrastructure business focused mainly on power-industry products and services.
Plans call for the headquarters of both companies to remain in Charlotte, housed in the current SPX building. It is unclear whether either company will retain the SPX name. SPX officials have not yet decided what either business will be called.







 Enlarge





                The two companies formed by SPX's proposed split would remain in Charlotte, sharing space… more 
NANCY PIERCE






 


"We ... believe this action will create significant value for our shareholders, customers and employees," SPX Chairman and CEO Chris Kearney told analysts during a conference call Wednesday. "We believe the spinoff will provide both companies greater flexibility to focus on and pursue their respective growth strategies."
Chief Financial Officer Jeremy Smeltser told analysts the deal is expected to be completed as soon as late July, although the transition could take as long as a year. The company expects to incur one-time costs of $60 million to $80 million because of the separation.
Leadership plan
Kearney will be chairman and chief executive of the new flow company. That will be the larger of the two new businesses, with annual revenue projected around $3 billion and earnings before taxes, interest, depreciation and amortization estimated at around $365 million.
Gene Lowe, now president of SPX's thermal segment, will be CEO of the Infrastructure company. He has been with SPX since 2008. Michael Mancuso, former chief financial officer of General Dynamics and an SPX board member since 2005, will be chairman of that company's board.
The infrastructure company would have revenue close to $2 billion and EBITDA around $130 million.
"The action accelerates our goal of creating a pure-play flow company that will be well-positioned as a leading provider of flow technologies across three broad end markets," Kearney said. "The remainder of SPX, the future infrastructure company, will also be well-positioned as a global infrastructure platform with market-leading positions."
Kearney and his team have been saying for several years now that SPX's future was in the flow operations, which provide processing systems for the food and beverage industry and pumps, valves and other key components for the oil, gas and electric power industries. The question has long been what would happen to SPX's other divisions.

Activist investors




 


When Kearney took over as CEO in 2004, SPX was at the start of divesting a number of businesses from a company that had grown into a sometimes-unwieldy conglomerate. The company has been focused for some time now on three basic units — flow technology, thermal equipment and industrial products. The last two units will form the new infrastructure company.
Kearney and Smeltser emphasized that the spinoff was the next logical step for the company. The company had been focusing on expanding its flow and thermal operations through late 2012. Then activist investment firm Relational Investors stepped in and started buying up large shares in SPX, criticizing what it called management's "growth at any costs" strategy.
SPX dropped out of negotiations for a major acquisition at that time (though the company never acknowledged the negotiations). It worked with Relational on strategy, even at one point offering to put members of Relational's choosing on the SPX board.
SPX focused more tightly on enhancing returns. And the spinoff appears designed to further that goal. Breaking the company in two divisions makes each piece freer to pursue individual growth strategies.
Clear plays
The separation also makes each company a clearer investment play in different industries.
One analyst on the call even suggested that the flow business could become an acquisition target, though Kearney and Smeltser emphasized that both new companies are being set up with capital and debt structures to be successful stand-alone businesses.
The considerations that led to the decision to divide the company appear similar to those that have Charlotte-based The Babcock & Wilcox Co. contemplating a similar move.
B&W (NYSE:BWC) is looking at separating its power-industry operations from its government contracting lines of business. Again in that case, there have been significant acquisitions by activist investors pressing for greater attention to shareholder returns. B&W, like SPX, has focused more on streamlining operations and is expected to disclose additional information about a possible separation of its basic business lines next week, when it announces its third-quarter earnings.







 




